06082nam a22007455i 9780889209275DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892092757 a10.51644/97808892092752doi  a(DE-B1597)667532  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPQ4416 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a80000aDante & the Unorthodox :bThe Aesthetics of Transgression /ced. by James Miller. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (576 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tRetheologizing Dante -- tTrapassar -- tDante’s Limbo -- tSaving Virgil -- tSacrificing Virgil -- tTrasmutar -- tDido Alighieri Gender Inversion in the Francesca Episode -- tFuming Accidie -- tHeresy and Politics in Inferno 10 -- tOriginal Skin Nudity and Obscenity in Dante’s Inferno -- tAnti-Dante -- tTrasumanar -- tRainbow Bodies -- tDante/Fante Embryology in Purgatory and Paradise -- tThe Cyprian Redeemed -- tTraslatar -- t“Dantescan Light” -- tEzra Pound in the Earthly Paradise -- tTralucere -- tDante and Cinema -- t“Moving Visual Thinking” -- tDriftworks, Pulseworks, Lightworks -- tTrasmodar -- tCalling Dante An Exhibition of Sculptures, Drawings, and Installations -- tCuratorial Essay Prophet of the Paragone -- tCalling Dante Notes on the Artists -- tCalling Dante From Dante on the Steps of Immortality -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring his lifetime, Dante was condemned as corrupt and banned from Florence on pain of death. But in 1329, eight years after his death, he was again viciously condemned—this time as a heretic and false prophet—by Friar Guido Vernani. From Vernani’s inquisitorial viewpoint, the author of the Commedia “seduced” his readers by offering them “a vessel of demonic poison” mixed with poetic fantasies designed to destroy the “healthful truth” of Catholicism. Thanks to such pious vituperations, a sulphurous fume of unorthodoxy has persistently clung to the mantle of Dante’s poetic fame. The primary critical purpose of Dante & the Unorthodox is to examine the aesthetic impulses behind the theological and political reasons for Dante’s allegory of mid-life divergence from the papally prescribed “way of salvation.” Marking the septicentennial of his exile, the book’s eighteen critical essays, three excerpts from an allegorical drama, and a portfolio of fourteen contemporary artworks address the issue of the poet’s conflicted relation to orthodoxy. By bringing the unorthodox out of the realm of “secret things,” by uncensoring them at every turn, Dante dared to oppose the censorious regime of Latin Christianity with a transgressive zeal more threatening to papal authority than the demonic hostility feared by Friar Vernani.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianisme dans la littérature. 0aChristianity in literature. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aReligion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aElder, R. Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeltham, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerhard, Mira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIannucci, Amilcare A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLund-Mead, Carolynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLachlan, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/